# GameNative — Advanced Game Performance Improvements

Implement all 10 tasks below in order. Each task is self-contained.
Read the full task before writing any code — the "Why" section explains
the root cause so you don't accidentally remove or weaken the fix.
All tasks must follow existing code patterns in the project.
Do not introduce new dependencies unless the task explicitly requires one.

## Plain terms — what each task does

| Task | In plain terms |
|------|----------------|
| **1 — CPU Affinity** | Pins the game process to big performance cores only. Without this the Android scheduler can put the game on small efficiency cores during a scene transition and cause a ~200ms stutter that looks like a GPU hitch but is a CPU scheduling decision. |
| **2 — Memory tuning** | Adds two sysctl values to the container init: `page-cluster=0` (kernel only decompresses the exact page needed for ZRAM) and `sched_migration_cost_ns` (game threads stay on the same core longer so cache stays warm). |
| **3 — Audio latency** | Default PulseAudio buffer is 200ms; the game's audio thread can block that long, which stalls the render thread and causes frame drops. Dropping to 60ms and 2 fragments removes that class of stutter. |
| **4 — Wine-GE** | Runtime picker in per-game settings. Games that crash on stock Wine can be switched to Wine-GE with hundreds of game-specific patches from Valve's Proton team. |
| **5 — ProtonDB badges** | Colored tier badge (Platinum/Gold/Silver/Bronze/Borked) on every game card from the ProtonDB community database so users know what will work before launching. |
| **6 — D8VK** | Covers classic DirectX 8 games (2000–2003) that otherwise use Wine's software renderer and run at single-digit FPS; D8VK translates DX8 to Vulkan. |
| **7 — Input polling** | Requests unbuffered input from Android for touch and gamepad so events arrive immediately instead of batched at 60Hz; on 120Hz+ devices this roughly halves input latency. |
| **8 — Huge pages** | Uses 2MB pages for Box64 JIT memory instead of 4KB, cutting TLB pressure on large open-world games where the JIT cache reaches 50–100MB. |
| **9 — Shader pre-warming** | Starts building the DXVK shader cache right after a game finishes downloading while the device is idle, so the first play session is smooth instead of stuttery. |
| **10 — VKD3D heap tuning** | Adds `force_static_cbv` to VKD3D config to reduce CPU cost per draw call and avoid descriptor heap reallocation spikes in large DX12 open-world titles. |

