## TASK 6 — D8VK (DirectX 8 → Vulkan)

### Why
DXVK handles DirectX 9, 10, and 11. VKD3D handles DirectX 12. But DirectX 8
games (many classic titles from 2000-2003) are not handled by either —
they fall through to Wine's software renderer which is extremely slow and
produces incorrect visuals. D8VK is a companion library to DXVK that
intercepts DX8 calls and translates them to Vulkan the same way DXVK
handles DX9-11. Installing D8VK alongside DXVK makes classic DX8 titles
run at full GPU speed.

### What to implement

D8VK ships as two DLL files: `d3d8.dll` and `d3d8.dll.so`.
They are deployed exactly the same way DXVK's DLLs are deployed.

In `DXVKHelper.java` (or the DXVK deployment code), after the DXVK
DLLs are copied into the Wine prefix's `system32` and `syswow64`
directories, also copy D8VK's `d3d8.dll`:

```java
// After DXVK deployment loop, add D8VK:
String[] d8vkDlls = {"d3d8.dll"};
for (String dll : d8vkDlls) {
    copyDllToWinePrefix(context, "d8vk/" + dll, winePrefix, dll);
}

// Register D8VK override so Wine uses it instead of built-in d3d8
// Add to the existing WINEDLLOVERRIDES value:
appendWineDllOverride(envVars, "d3d8=n,b");
```

Store the D8VK DLL in `assets/d8vk/d3d8.dll` — download the latest
D8VK ARM64-compatible build from the d8vk GitHub releases and add it
to the project assets.

