## TASK 7 — High-Rate Input Polling

### Why
Android polls touch and gamepad input at 60Hz by default, regardless of
the display refresh rate. This means even on a 144Hz display, input events
arrive at most 60 times per second — 16ms of input latency floor.
`requestUnbufferedDispatch` tells Android to deliver input events to the
app immediately when the hardware samples them, bypassing the normal
batching. On devices with 120Hz+ displays that support high-rate input
sampling (most 2022+ flagships), this can halve input latency.

### What to implement

In `XServerScreen.kt`, add this inside the composable where the
`LocalView` or `LocalWindow` is accessible:

```kotlin
// Request unbuffered input dispatch for lower latency
// This tells Android to deliver touch/input events immediately
// without waiting to batch them — critical for gaming
val view = LocalView.current
LaunchedEffect(Unit) {
    if (Build.VERSION.SDK_INT >= Build.VERSION_CODES.TIRAMISU) {
        // API 33+ supports per-class unbuffered dispatch
        view.requestUnbufferedDispatch(InputDevice.SOURCE_TOUCHSCREEN)
        view.requestUnbufferedDispatch(InputDevice.SOURCE_GAMEPAD)
        view.requestUnbufferedDispatch(InputDevice.SOURCE_JOYSTICK)
    } else if (Build.VERSION.SDK_INT >= Build.VERSION_CODES.LOLLIPOP) {
        // Older API — request for all MotionEvents
        @Suppress("DEPRECATION")
        view.requestUnbufferedDispatch(MotionEvent.obtain(0, 0, MotionEvent.ACTION_MOVE, 0f, 0f, 0))
    }
}
```

Also set the input thread priority in the container startup script:
```bash
# Raise input thread priority inside container
renice -n -5 -p $(pgrep -f "wine" | head -1) 2>/dev/null || true
```

