## TASK 8 — Transparent Huge Pages for Box64

### Why
Box64's JIT compiler allocates large contiguous blocks of memory to store
translated ARM64 code. By default, Linux manages these blocks using 4KB
pages, which means a 64MB JIT cache requires 16,384 separate page table
entries. Each memory access to a new page is a potential TLB miss, which
stalls the CPU. Transparent Huge Pages (THP) automatically uses 2MB pages
instead of 4KB for large allocations — reducing TLB misses by up to 512x
for JIT memory. On large open-world games with extensive JIT caches,
this is a measurable win.

`BOX64_DYNAREC_ALIGNED_ATOMICS=1` tells Box64 to emit ARM64 aligned
atomic instructions instead of the slower emulated x86 atomic semantics.
Pairs with THP because aligned atomics work best with 2MB-aligned memory.

### What to implement

In `GuestProgramLauncherComponent.java`, add to the existing sysctl
script block AFTER the other sysctl calls:

```bash
echo always > /sys/kernel/mm/transparent_hugepage/enabled 2>/dev/null || true;
echo defer+madvise > /sys/kernel/mm/transparent_hugepage/defrag 2>/dev/null || true;
```

In `BionicProgramLauncherComponent.java` and
`GlibcProgramLauncherComponent.java`, add to the Box64 env vars section
(alongside existing BOX64_DYNAREC_BIGBLOCK etc.):

```java
envVars.put("BOX64_DYNAREC_ALIGNED_ATOMICS", "1");
```

