## TASK 9 — Shader Pre-Warming After Download

### Why
Currently the DXVK shader state cache builds during the FIRST play session.
Even with async compilation enabled, the first 5-10 minutes of a new game
have micro-stutter as thousands of new shaders are encountered and queued
for async compilation. The fix is to start building the shader cache
IMMEDIATELY after the game finishes downloading, while the device is idle,
so the first actual play session has a warm cache.

### What to implement

In the download completion handler (wherever download finished is detected,
likely in `DownloadService` or `SteamService`):

```kotlin
fun onDownloadComplete(appId: Int) {
    // Existing download complete logic...

    // Trigger shader pre-warming in background
    if (shouldPreWarmShaders(appId)) {
        WorkManager.getInstance(context).enqueueUniqueWork(
            "shaderPreWarm_$appId",
            ExistingWorkPolicy.KEEP,
            buildShaderPreWarmWork(appId)
        )
    }
}

fun buildShaderPreWarmWork(appId: Int): OneTimeWorkRequest {
    return OneTimeWorkRequestBuilder<ShaderPreWarmWorker>()
        .setInputData(workDataOf("appId" to appId))
        .setConstraints(
            Constraints.Builder()
                .setRequiresCharging(false)      // run anytime, not just charging
                .setRequiresBatteryNotLow(true)  // don't run when battery is critical
                .build()
        )
        .build()
}
```

Create `ShaderPreWarmWorker.kt`:

```kotlin
class ShaderPreWarmWorker(
    context: Context,
    params: WorkerParameters
) : CoroutineWorker(context, params) {

    override suspend fun doWork(): Result {
        val appId = inputData.getInt("appId", -1)
        if (appId == -1) return Result.failure()

        return withContext(Dispatchers.IO) {
            try {
                // Run the game executable once headlessly with a null display
                // so DXVK initializes its state cache without rendering anything.
                // The game will fail to open a window (no display) and exit quickly,
                // but DXVK will have scanned the executable and pre-populated
                // its pipeline state cache entries.
                val gameExe = GamePaths.getGameExecutable(applicationContext, appId)
                if (gameExe != null) {
                    ContainerUtils.runCommand(
                        "DISPLAY= DXVK_LOG_LEVEL=none wine \"$gameExe\" --help 2>/dev/null || true"
                    )
                }
                Result.success()
            } catch (e: Exception) {
                Result.failure()
            }
        }
    }
}
```

Show a subtle indicator in the library grid that shaders are being
pre-warmed — a small animated progress indicator replacing the status
chip on the game card while the WorkManager job is running. Use
`WorkManager.getWorkInfosForUniqueWorkLiveData` to observe the job state.

