## TASK 10 — VKD3D Descriptor Heap and DX12 Tuning

### Why
In DirectX 12, games allocate large descriptor heaps to hold references
to textures, buffers, and render targets. VKD3D-Proton maps these to
Vulkan descriptor sets. For large open-world games (Cyberpunk 2077,
Elden Ring, RDR2 in DX12 mode), the default descriptor heap fills up
and VKD3D must reallocate it mid-frame — this causes a GPU pipeline stall
that shows up as a 50-150ms frame spike.

`force_static_cbv` tells VKD3D to use static constant buffer descriptors
instead of dynamic ones. Static descriptors have lower CPU overhead per
draw call and reduce descriptor heap pressure significantly in games that
update constant buffers every frame.

### What to implement

In `DXVKHelper.java` (or `vkd3d.env`), find the existing
`VKD3D_CONFIG` value and APPEND `force_static_cbv` to it.
Do NOT replace the existing value — append with a comma:

```java
// Find existing VKD3D_CONFIG value and append force_static_cbv
String existingVkd3dConfig = envVars.getOrDefault(
    "VKD3D_CONFIG",
    "pipeline_library_app_cache,no_upload_hvv"
);
if (!existingVkd3dConfig.contains("force_static_cbv")) {
    envVars.put("VKD3D_CONFIG", existingVkd3dConfig + ",force_static_cbv");
}

// Disable descriptor QA checks — these are developer debugging tools
// that add CPU overhead in every draw call. Always off in release.
envVars.put("VKD3D_DESCRIPTOR_QA_CHECKS", "0");
```

Also add VKD3D shader model cap to avoid DX12 SM6.6+ shader compilation
failures on older Turnip versions:
```java
// Cap shader model at SM 6.5 — SM 6.6+ features are rarely used by games
// and Turnip 23.x has incomplete SM 6.6 support that causes crashes
envVars.put("VKD3D_SHADER_MODEL", "6_5");
```

